<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Josiefuz on 12-13-2001 08:57 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Frankly I don't see why all the heat in this discussion.  The zone was broke, they threw a tourniquet on it to buy time to fix it properly.  Was the short-term fix too much?  Certainly, but it bought them the extra day they needed to make changes and re-test it.  The follow-up fix seems to be reasonable, and they've already said they'd tweak it more if it still wasn't right.

No one can test a product like end-users.  I build databases for a living, and no amount of testing can *ever* replace 1000 end-users beating on the system (and Verant has 200,000 end-users).  No product is ever 100% ready for release.  It's best to get it to 80% and then push it out the door.  This is even more true with a product that patches itself.

Equating EQ to a published work (book, board game, etc) isn't appropriate.  Reprinting a book is a lot different than tossing out an electronic patch.

While I don't excuse Verant of their errors, I do aplaud the rate at which they are fixing the problems.  

-Fuz
59 Templar, Sol Ro
</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
